{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:19:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14106"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14106"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.5,0.23,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6776"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of gout diagnosed two years ago. He has a medical history of hypertension and obesity. His regular medications include allopurinol (300mg daily for the past six months) and amlodipine. He reports having frequent gout flares in the past six months. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits and he is afebrile. There are visible tophi on his elbows, knees and feet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate serum urate target for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u003C0.20 mmol/L","\u003C0.26 mmol/L","\u003C0.30 mmol/L","\u003C0.36 mmol/L","\u003C0.40 mmol/L"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor this patient with frequent flares of gout and visible tophi, the most appropriate serum urate target is \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.30 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E. This lower target is recommended for patients with tophaceous gout to promote more rapid dissolution of urate crystals and resolution of tophi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe target of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.36 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is generally considered adequate for patients with uncomplicated gout without tophi. However, this target is not sufficiently low for patients with tophaceous gout. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA target of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.26 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.20 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily low and difficult to achieve in most patients. While these levels might lead to faster resolution of tophi, they also increase the risk of side effects from higher doses of urate-lowering therapy without providing significant additional clinical benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe target of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;0.40 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E is too high for effective management of gout, especially in a patient with tophi. At this level, urate crystals would continue to form and existing tophi would not resolve effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that achieving and maintaining the target serum urate level often requires ongoing monitoring and adjustment of urate-lowering therapy. In this case, the patient is on allopurinol 300 mg daily, which may need to be adjusted based on his serum urate levels. Regular follow-up and serum urate testing are essential to ensure that the target is being maintained and to adjust treatment as necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The target serum urate level for patients with gout and visible tophi is \u003C0.30 mmol/L.","Patients with gout and tophi require more aggressive urate-lowering therapy to achieve dissolution of urate crystals.","Regular monitoring of serum urate levels is essential in managing gout, especially when adjusting urate-lowering therapy."],"references":["Robinson P, Stamp L. The management of gout: Much has changed. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2016;45:299-302. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14106"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T15:34:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T17:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":n